cumentary … from a historical perspective -- t14. Towards behavioural realism: experiments in immersive journalism -- t15. Interactive documentary and live performance: from embodied to emplaced interaction -- t16. The travelling i-doc: reflections on the meaning of interactive documentary-based image-making practices in contemporary India -- t17. Interactive documentary aquí y ahora – here & now: themes and directions in South America -- t18. Who wants to become banal?: the i-doc from experiment to industry -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of documentary has been one of adaptation and change, as docu-mentarists have harnessed the affordances of emerging technology. In the last decade interactive documentaries (i-docs) have become established as a new field of practice within non-fiction storytelling. Their various incarnations are now a focus at leading film festivals (IDFA DocLab, Tribeca Storyscapes, Sheffield DocFest), major international awards have been won, and they are increasingly the subject of academic study. This anthology looks at the creative practices, purposes and ethics that lie behind these emergent forms. Expert contributions, case studies and interviews with major figures in the field address the production processes that lie behind interactive documentary, as well as the political, cultural and geographic contexts in which they are emerging and the media ecology that supports them. Taking a broad view of interactive documentary as any work which engages with 'the real' by employing digital interactive technology, this volume addresses a range of platforms and environments, from web-docs and virtual reality to mobile media and live performance. It thus explores the challenges that face interactive documentary practitioners and scholars, and proposes new ways of producing and engaging with interactive factual content.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDocumentary mass media. 0aInteractive multimedia. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Christopher Cekay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAston, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAston, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDovey, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFavero, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGantier, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaudenzi, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaudenzi, Sandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGifreu-Castells, Arnau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHight, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapur, Anandana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabour, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinington, Jess, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoskowitz, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNash, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPringle, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Mandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Mandy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUricchio, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiehl, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinston, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov